2021Q4 and 2022Q1 saw 305,840 and 305,407 vehicles produces, respectively. For "at least 330,000" vehicles to be produced in 2022Q2, output needs to increase by 24,593, or approximately 8.05%. With production at Gigafactory Berlin having begun in March 2022, and Gigafactory Texas delivering finished vehicles in April 2022, this may be achievable. Both plants produce Tesla Model Y vehicles, and their production numbers are not included in the 2022Q1 10-Q report available on the Tesla Investor Relations website. If production at the Fremont, CA factory can be increased for the series of vehicles it produces, even slightly, along with steady production from the Berlin and Texas Gigafactories, this is achievable.The operation status of the Shanghai Gigafactory is not factored in with the analysis. If it is producing vehicles, then that will only help increase the likelihood of Tesla meeting the "goal" of this forecasting question.

Further details on plans for Tesla to reopen Monday, April 18: "$TSLA appears ready to restart production in Giga Shanghai on Monday with at least one shift, increasing to two shifts by end of April." With link to WSJ article: https://twitter.com/garyblack00/status/1515342044222349319 So, it looks like the factory will likely be operating during 1 shift for most of the rest of the month. It's not completely clear to me how many shifts it ordinarily has, but if it has 4, then each day at 1/4 capacity would result in a loss of production of ~1814 vehicles. So, as I wrote yesterday, it looks like for April, Tesla Giga Shanghai will have at least 17 closed days, resulting in a loss of ~41.1k vehicles, plus a loss of ~1.81k(?) for every day it remains at 1 shift, and ~1.2k(?) for every day at 2 shifts. If it is only open 1 shift per day for 10 days, that would potentially mean a loss of production of ~41.1k + ~18.1k = ~59.2k vehicles. And then there would be some days with only 2 shifts operating. And this all seems a bit optimistic. Even if Tesla could ordinarily have reached 380k in Q1 without Shanghai Covid lockdowns, which is beyond the most optimistic numbers I saw before the Covid situation in Shanghai came up, it wouldn't be able to make 330k now.

Repeating my forecast. The Covid lockdown situation in Shanghai remains extremely serious, and the lockdown has been extended "indefinitely." Reported cases are still increasing daily and were over 21k yesterday. The Shanghai Giga factory operates 24/7. If it misses 13 days of operation, not producing 330k in Q2 is all but assured. Giga has already been closed 8 days. It's extremely hard to see how it won't be closed at least 5 more days in Q2, and possibly many more beyond that. Far smaller outbreaks in other cities have led to weeks of lockdowns. Moreover, Shanghai's outbreak tests the limits of China's zero Covid policy, which has been showcased by the regime as a successful strategy. A lot is at stake here, from people's health to the Chinese and world economy to a central policy and point of pride of the regime. I think there is little chance that the Tesla factory will reopen early in this context.

Been waffling on this one because I couldn't figure out where the 330,000 threshold was coming from, the question felt like a trap. Credit to @belikewater for the delivery forecast link, I feel like I actually have a well-informed outside rate now, the Q2 forecast there with the historic -3% accounted for would be ~322k. Each day of lockdown in Shanghai cuts ~2k vehicles, and the Jilin lockdown was multiple weeks long. The outside rate on this was already sub-50% (unless posting realistically but not exaggeratedly low production forecasts is an elaborate April fools joke), so lockdowns bring that down lower. That said, I'm not sure if Shanghai lockdowns are being priced into the forecast numbers already. Will need to keep watching this one. Also, Tesla forecasted >50% growth in 2022, if that applies quarter-by-quarter then 50% over Q22021 would be ~309k, then there's some small bump above that for the >, so the numbers here at least seem internally consistent.

If it weren't for Covid, I think this question would be a slam-dunk yes. I'm moving my forecast down a little lower because of the Shanghai lockdowns, which have been expanded. It's hard to see how lockdowns won't also be extended with increasing local cases. One projection I've seen is for ~369k vehicles produced in Q2; this estimate is from someone whose recent quarterly estimates have been off by only -3.1% to -2.6%. (If his Q2 estimate is off by -3.1%, the actual value would be 380k.) If all else goes well elsewhere, and if this projection would otherwise be true, then there's about 39k wiggle room on this forecast. As I understand it, Tesla operates its Shanghai factory 24/7 and makes "over 50k" vehicles/month (and growing). So it could withstand approximately 24 days of shutdown and still make it to 330k. I could picture 24 days of lockdowns closing the Shanghai factory, though. Other provinces, e.g., Jilin, have been locked down until it's been 14 days since the last case has been detected, but that rule may not be adhered to in Shanghai. I've also heard rumors about Tesla workers living in company housing on site or taking company buses and that production could continue that way, too. Some financial traders working for banks are being asked to live at work during the lockdowns. So, I'm keeping my forecast relatively high for now, but watching and waiting. I agree with @Eolienne that the situation in Shanghai could potentially have a big impact on this question.

The 305, 840 vehicles Tesla produced in 4th quarter 2021 far exceeded what was produced in the third quarter (237,000) and was also above Wall Street projections (265,000) (https://electrek.co/2022/01/02/tesla-tsla-record-q4-2021-production-deliveries-electric-cars/). It was the highest quarterly production by Tesla thus far. Wall Street projections for 1st Quarter 2022 are 296,000 (https://www.barrons.com/articles/tesla-stock-deliveries-outlook-2022-51640898832). It seems the Wall Street projection has assimilated the larger number of the previous quarter into its numbers. I have a strong tendency to think the production number for this coming quarter will continue to climb but can find nothing supporting that this may be the case. I’m indeterminate. Wall Street projections are not reliable indicators, nor is past performance been standard to the point that it is easy to understand if Tesla production will continue to rise or regress towards a mean.
Checking myself in lieu of wrecking myself (or others...) will review and return: https://www.linkedin.com/news/story/covid-shuts-down-tesla-factory-5780106/

Production targets cover this number. Of course, shortages in key ingredients have hampered production at other automakers this past year, however has been largely spared by keeping a big inventory of parts. With sustained problems, these problems could grow. However, given the output of the last few quarters and sustaining the current growth trend, these numbers are very much achievable. New car demand is on the return and new offers are being happily picked up by consumers right now, this doesn't immediately concern this question but gives a good rationale for meeting targets in the second quarter if that can be facilitated.

3/17: Current production capacity (Texas & China) is estimated over 1M units/year. There are two new plants close to opening; one is expected to be online Q1. With this additional plant, it is likely Tesla could achieve this number. They have also made some design changes in response to supply constraints though I expect that these will be a limited factor in achieving the 330K.

Not doubt Tesla was planning for this level, but there are some limitations now out there. Chip shortages and raw ingredients for production are going to start getting tighter and more expensive due to the amount of things that come from Russia and that need an alternative source due to sanctions.
